data.content:
## What happened

In C# 14, new built-in span conversions change overload resolution. `array.Contains(num)` now binds to **`MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)`** instead of `Enumerable.Contains(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. Expression trees can't represent span-based methods, so it throws at runtime.

## Fix

Force the compiler to pick the `IEnumerable<T>` overload:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast the array to IEnumerable<int>
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: Use Enumerable.Contains explicitly
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

The same issue affects `Reverse()` on arrays (now resolves to the in-place `Span` version). Apply the same pattern: use `.AsEnumerable()`, cast to `IEnumerable<T>`, or call `Enumerable.Reverse(arr)` explicitly.
